#Text=The Hungry Man was Fed
#Text=Young Van Bibber broke one of his rules of life one day and came down-town .
#Text=This unusual journey into the marts of trade and finance was in response to a call from his lawyer , who wanted his signature to some papers .
#Text=It was five years since Van Bibber had been south of the north side of Washington Square , except as a transient traveller to the ferries on the elevated road .

#Text=And as he walked through the City Hall Square he looked about him at the new buildings in the air , and the bustle and confusion of the streets , with as much interest as a lately arrived immigrant .
#Text=He rather enjoyed the novelty of the situation , and after he had completed his business at the lawyer 's office he tried to stroll along lower Broadway as he did on the Avenue .

#Text=But people bumped against him , and carts and drays tried to run him down when he crossed the side streets , and those young men whom he knew seemed to be in a great hurry , and expressed such amused surprise at seeing him that he felt very much out of place indeed .
#Text=And so he decided to get back to his club window and its quiet as soon as possible .
#Text=" Hello , Van Bibber , " said one of the young men who were speeding by , " what brings you here ?

column3:
_	_	_	_

#Text= I think I have , " said Van Bibber .

column1: #Text=" If you 'll kindly tell me how I can get back to civilization again , be obliged to you . "
#Text=" Take the elevated from Park Place , " said his friend from over his shoulder , as he nodded and dived into the crowd .
#Text=The visitor from up-town had not a very distinct idea as to where Park Place was , but he struck off Broadway and followed the line of the elevated road along Church Street .
#Text=It was at the corner of Vesey Street that a miserable-looking , dirty , and red-eyed object stood still in his tracks and begged Van Bibber for a few cents to buy food .
#Text=" I 've come all the way from Chicago , " said the Object , " and I have n't tasted food for twenty-four hours . "
#Text=Van Bibber drew away as though the Object had a contagious disease in his rags , and handed him a quarter without waiting to receive the man 's blessing .
#Text=" Poor devil ! " said Van Bibber .
#Text=" Fancy going without dinner all day ! "
#Text=He could not fancy this , though he tried , and the impossibility of it impressed him so much that he amiably determined to go back and hunt up the Object and give him more money .
#Text=Van Bibber 's ideas of a dinner were rather exalted .
#Text=He did not know of places where a quarter was good for a " square meal , " including " one roast , three vegetables , and pie . "
#Text=He hardly considered a quarter a sufficiently large tip for the waiter who served the dinner , and decidedly not enough for the dinner itself .
#Text=He did not see his man at first , and when he did the man did not see him .
#Text=Van Bibber watched him stop three gentlemen , two of whom gave him some money , and then the Object approached Van Bibber and repeated his sad tale in a monotone .

#Text=He evidently did not recognize Van Bibber , and the clubman gave him a half-dollar and walked away , feeling that the man must surely have enough by this time with which to get something to eat , if only a luncheon .
#Text=This retracing of his footsteps had confused Van Bibber , and he made a complete circuit of the block before he discovered that he had lost his bearings .
#Text=He was standing just where he had started , and gazing along the line of the elevated road , looking for a station , when the familiar accents of the Object again saluted him .
#Text=When Van Bibber faced him the beggar looked uneasy .

#Text=He was not sure whether or not he had approached this particular gentleman before , but Van Bibber conceived an idea of much subtlety , and deceived the Object by again putting his hand in his pocket .
#Text=" Nothing to eat for twenty-four hours !

#Text= Have n't you any money , either ? "

column1: #Text=" Not a cent , " groaned the Object , " an ' I 'm just faint for food , sir .

column3:
_	_	_	_

#Text= Well , " said Van Bibber , suddenly , " if it is just something to eat you want , come in here with me and I 'll give you your breakfast . "

column1: #Text=But the man held back and began to whine and complain that they would n't let the likes of him in such a fine place .
#Text=" Oh , yes , they will , " said Van Bibber , glancing at the bill of fare in front of the place .
#Text=" It seems to be extremely cheap .

#Text=Go in ,  he added , and there was something in his tone which made the Object move ungraciously into the eating-house .

column1: #Text=The Object looked uneasy , and Van Bibber , who stood beside his chair , smiled in triumph .
